Python Notes: String, List, Tuple, and Dictionary

1. String

A string is a sequence of characters used to store text. A string may contain letters, numbers, spaces, and symbols. Strings are written inside single, double, or triple quotation marks.

Properties of strings

Ordered: Every character has a fixed position.

Indexed: The first character has index 0.

Immutable: Individual characters cannot be changed after the string is created.

Case-sensitive: Uppercase and lowercase letters are treated differently.

Duplicates allowed: A character may appear more than once.

Iterable: A string can be processed one character at a time.

String concatenation

Concatenation means joining strings together. The plus operator is commonly used for concatenation. A number must first be converted into a string before it can be joined directly with text.

String indexing

Indexing accesses one character from a string.

Positive indexing starts from 0 and moves from left to right.

Negative indexing starts from -1 and moves from right to left.

String slicing

Slicing extracts a section of a string.

Syntax: string[start:stop:step]

start is the first included position.

stop is the ending position and is not included.

step controls how many positions to move at a time.

A negative step can reverse a string.

Print formatting

Print formatting combines text and values in a readable way.

.format() method

The .format() method places values into curly-brace placeholders.

Syntax: "Text {}".format(value)

It supports:

Positional placeholders

Named placeholders

Decimal formatting

Percentage formatting

Number alignment

Thousands separators

F-string

An f-string places variable names or expressions directly inside curly braces. It is a modern and readable formatting method.

Syntax: f"Text {variable}"

Locating and counting string content

find() returns the index of the first match. It returns -1 when the value is missing.

index() returns the index of the first match. It raises an error when the value is missing.

rfind() returns the position of the last match.

count() returns the number of times a character or word appears.

String checking methods

These methods return either True or False.

isalnum() checks whether the string contains only letters and numbers.

isalpha() checks whether the string contains only letters.

isdigit() checks whether the string contains only digits.

istitle() checks whether each word begins with a capital letter and the remaining letters are lowercase.

islower() checks whether all letters are lowercase.

isupper() checks whether all letters are uppercase.

isspace() checks whether the string contains only whitespace.

startswith() checks whether the string starts with a specified value.

endswith() checks whether the string ends with a specified value.

Other important string methods

upper() converts letters to uppercase.

lower() converts letters to lowercase.

title() changes text to title case.

capitalize() capitalizes the first character.

strip() removes whitespace from both ends.

replace() replaces selected text.

split() divides a string into a list and removes the separator.

partition() divides a string into a three-item tuple: text before the separator, the separator, and text after it.

expandtabs() replaces tab characters with spaces according to a selected tab size.

