partition() is a string method, not a regular expression.

2. List

A list is an ordered collection that stores multiple items in one variable. Lists are written using square brackets.

Properties of lists

Ordered: Items retain their positions.

Indexed: The first item has index 0.

Mutable: Items can be added, removed, or changed.

Duplicates allowed: The same value may appear more than once.

Mixed data types allowed: A list can contain strings, numbers, Boolean values, and other collections.

Dynamic: A list can grow or shrink.

List indexing

Indexing accesses one item from a list.

Positive indexing begins at 0.

Negative indexing begins at -1 from the end.

List slicing

Slicing extracts a section and returns a new list.

Syntax: list[start:stop:step]

The stop position is not included. A negative step can reverse the order.

List mutability

Mutability means list items can be changed after creation. Items can also be inserted, appended, or removed.

Important list methods

append() adds one item to the end.

extend() adds each item from another collection.

insert() adds an item at a specified index.

pop() removes and returns an item; without an index, it removes the last item.

remove() removes the first matching value.

reverse() reverses the original list.

sort() arranges the original list in ascending or descending order.

count() counts occurrences of a value.

index() returns the first index of a value.

clear() removes all items.

copy() creates a shallow copy.

append() versus extend()

append() adds its argument as one complete item.

extend() adds the argument's individual items separately.

remove() versus pop()

remove() deletes an item by value.

pop() deletes an item by index and returns the removed item.

Nested list

A nested list is a list containing one or more lists. Multiple indexes are used to access an item inside an inner list. Nested lists are useful for tables, matrices, student records, and grouped data.

List comprehension

List comprehension is a short method for creating a new list from an existing iterable. It can transform items and include a condition.

Basic syntax: [expression for item in collection]

Conditional syntax: [expression for item in collection if condition]

3. Tuple

A tuple is an ordered collection used to store multiple values. Tuples are usually written using parentheses. The comma is what technically creates a tuple.

Properties of tuples

Ordered: Items retain their positions.

Indexed: The first item has index 0.

Immutable: Items cannot be added, removed, or changed directly.

Duplicates allowed: Values may appear more than once.

Mixed data types allowed: A tuple can contain different kinds of data.

One-item tuple

A one-item tuple requires a comma after its item. Without the comma, Python treats the value as its ordinary data type rather than a tuple.

Tuple indexing and slicing

Tuples support positive and negative indexing. They also use the same slicing structure as strings and lists.

Syntax: tuple[start:stop:step]

Slicing returns a new tuple and does not modify the original tuple.

Tuple methods

Tuples have only two main methods because they are immutable:

count() counts how many times a value appears.

index() returns the position of the first matching value.

Tuple packing

Tuple packing means combining multiple values into one tuple.

Tuple unpacking

Tuple unpacking means assigning tuple values to separate variables. The number of variables normally needs to match the number of tuple items. A starred variable can collect remaining items.

Nested tuple

A nested tuple contains another tuple. Multiple indexes are used to reach an item inside the inner tuple.

When to use a tuple

Use a tuple for information that should remain fixed, such as coordinates, months, fixed settings, or constant records.

4. Dictionary

A dictionary stores information as key-value pairs. Dictionaries are written using curly brackets. Each key identifies its related value.

Properties of dictionaries

Ordered: Modern Python dictionaries retain insertion order.

Mutable: Key-value pairs can be added, changed, or removed.

Key-based: Values are accessed with keys rather than numerical positions.

Unique keys: A key cannot appear more than once; a later duplicate replaces the earlier value.

Duplicate values allowed: Different keys may contain the same value.

Mixed data types allowed: Values can contain any data type.

Dictionary keys

Keys must be immutable and hashable, such as strings, numbers, or suitable tuples. Lists and dictionaries cannot be used as keys because they are mutable.

Accessing values

Square-bracket access retrieves the value associated with a key but raises an error if the key is missing.

get() retrieves a value safely and can return a chosen default when the key is missing.

Adding and changing information

Assigning a value to a new key adds a key-value pair. Assigning a new value to an existing key updates that pair.

Important dictionary methods

get() safely retrieves a value.

keys() returns all keys.

values() returns all values.

items() returns all key-value pairs.

update() adds new pairs or changes existing pairs.

pop() removes a specified key and returns its value.

popitem() removes and returns the last inserted pair.

clear() removes all pairs.

copy() creates a shallow copy.

setdefault() returns a key's value or adds the key with a default value.

fromkeys() creates a dictionary from a group of keys with one default value.

Checking dictionary membership

The in and not in operators check keys by default. To check values, membership must be checked in the dictionary's values collection.

Nested dictionary

A nested dictionary is a dictionary containing another dictionary. It is useful for structured information such as multiple student, employee, customer, or product records.

List of dictionaries

A list of dictionaries stores several structured records. Each dictionary represents one record, while the list stores the complete group.

Dictionary comprehension

Dictionary comprehension is a short way to construct a dictionary from an iterable.

Basic syntax: {key_expression: value_expression for item in collection}

